     1Ôćĺ# Technical Design Document
     2Ôćĺ
     3ÔćĺThere are two principal systems in play: the chat application, and the game state. The two pass well-defined messages to tightly-bound interfaces in a "mailbox" model.
     4Ôćĺ
     5Ôćĺ## Application Layer
     6Ôćĺ
     7ÔćĺThis layer comprises the basic Create and Read actions the user can perform in the chat application. It involves three main sections: A chat selector on the left side, an active chat on the right, which comprises a chat component and an input component. Because of the limited nature of this experience, this system should be as simple and involve as little abstraction as possible. It should provide the following interface to the Game State.
     8Ôćĺ
     9Ôćĺ```typescript
    10Ôćĺinterface ChatUser = {
    11Ôćĺ    name: string;
    12Ôćĺ    profilePicture: Image;
    13Ôćĺ    status: "active" | "away" | "busy" | "offline";
    14Ôćĺ    statusText: Markdown;
    15Ôćĺ}
    16Ôćĺtype ChatAppState = {
    17Ôćĺ    chats: ChatComponentState[];
    18Ôćĺ    player : ChatUser;
    19Ôćĺ    // 0-index of currently selected chat
    20Ôćĺ    currentlySelected : number;
    21Ôćĺ}
    22Ôćĺ// Game layer tightly binds to this to send messages as the "partners"
    23Ôćĺfunction appendPartnerMessage (userIndex: number; message: Markdown) : void;
    24Ôćĺ```
    25Ôćĺ
    26Ôćĺ### Chat component
    27Ôćĺ
    28ÔćĺEach "chat" should be an instance of a component, which is a data-dependent renderer of a list of chat objects. It should, provided a list of these objects, render the chat, including timestamps, and profile pictures/usernames in between changes in the chat.
    29Ôćĺ
    30Ôćĺ```typescript
    31Ôćĺtype ChatComponentState = ChatUser & {
    32Ôćĺ    messsages: {
    33Ôćĺ        role: "user" | "partner";
    34Ôćĺ        text: Markdown;
    35Ôćĺ        time: UTCTime;
    36Ôćĺ    }[];
    37Ôćĺ};
    38Ôćĺ```
    39Ôćĺ
    40Ôćĺ### Selector component
    41Ôćĺ
    42ÔćĺThere should be one selector component, which is responsible for tracking the currently selected chat. It should list all available chats, the last message sent in each of them, as well as the username, profile picture, status indicator, and other expected information about the chat. The currently selected chat should also be highlighted the active chat, and clicking on another chat should select that chat.
    43Ôćĺ
    44Ôćĺ### Input Component
    45Ôćĺ
    46ÔćĺThe input component is omnipresent, and involves an input field in which the user can compose their message. Once the user sends the message, the Input Component should both update the currently selected chat component with the user's new message, _and_ forward the message and currently selected partner to the Game State (see below).
    47Ôćĺ
    48Ôćĺ## Game State
    49Ôćĺ
    50ÔćĺThe Game State comprises the logic of the game. It exposes the following interface to the Application Layer:
    51Ôćĺ
    52Ôćĺ```typescript
    53Ôćĺfunction recieveMessage(message: { userIndex: number; text: Markdown }): void {
    54Ôćĺ    // Never respond unless it's the assistant user.
    55Ôćĺ    if (userIndex !== assistantUser) return;
    56Ôćĺ    GameState.incomingMessages.push(stripMarkdown(message.text));
    57Ôćĺ    // Kick off the message processing loop. notably DOES NOT AWAIT; we don't want to block recieving more user messages.
    58Ôćĺ    GameState.processMessageQueue();
    59Ôćĺ}
    60Ôćĺ```
    61Ôćĺ
    62Ôćĺ```typescript
    63Ôćĺtype GameState = { };
    64Ôćĺ
    65Ôćĺ//Singleton state instance, mutated
    66Ôćĺexport default const state : GameState;
    67Ôćĺ
    68Ôćĺexport const incomingMessages: string[];
    69Ôćĺ
    70Ôćĺ// Scenes are generally imported from specific scene files.
    71Ôćĺtype Scene = () => undefined | Promise<Markdown>;
    72Ôćĺconst sceneList : Scene[] = [];
    73Ôćĺvar currentlyRunningScene : boolean = true;
    74Ôćĺ
    75Ôćĺfunction processMessageQueue(){
    76Ôćĺ    if(currentlyRunningScene) return;
    77Ôćĺ    currentlyRunningScene = true;
    78Ôćĺ    while(R.notEmpty(incomingMessages)){
    79Ôćĺ        const currentMessage = incomingMessages.shift();
    80Ôćĺ        for(scene in sceneList){
    81Ôćĺ            const mbRunner = scene();
    82Ôćĺ            if(mbRunner != null) {
    83Ôćĺ                Chat.appendPartnerMessage(assistantUser, await runner);
    84Ôćĺ                break;
    85Ôćĺ            }
    86Ôćĺ        }
    87Ôćĺ    }
    88Ôćĺ    currentlyRunningScene = false;
    89Ôćĺ}
    90Ôćĺ```
    91Ôćĺ
    92ÔćĺAdditionally, during development, buttons should be available to copy and paste state to and from the clipboard, and every change to the state should be logged, and the state should be able to be visually explored.
    93Ôćĺ
    94Ôćĺ## Scene
    95Ôćĺ
    96ÔćĺScenes generally live in their own modules, with the following pattern:
    97Ôćĺ
    98Ôćĺ```typescript
    99Ôćĺ// use a builder to prevent accidental state mutations
   100Ôćĺexport const createSceneState = () => ({
   101Ôćĺ    "..."
   102Ôćĺ})
   103Ôćĺ
   104Ôćĺexport const shouldTrigger: Scene = () => checkCondition ? runScene() : null;
   105Ôćĺ
   106Ôćĺasync function runScene(){
   107Ôćĺ    ///do the actual scene stuff
   108Ôćĺ}
   109Ôćĺ```
   110Ôćĺ
   111Ôćĺ## Synonym System
   112Ôćĺ
   113ÔćĺThe Synonym System is a system that helps Scenes in the Game Layer avoid repetitive, stilted content. It exposes the following interface:
   114Ôćĺ
   115Ôćĺ```typescript
   116Ôćĺtype SynonymCorpus = {
   117Ôćĺ    [key: string]: Synonym<any>;
   118Ôćĺ};
   119Ôćĺ
   120Ôćĺtype Synonym<Sources> = {
   121Ôćĺ    synonyms: [(Sources) => string];
   122Ôćĺ    currentIndex: number;
   123Ôćĺ};
   124Ôćĺ
   125Ôćĺtype Synonym<undefined> = {
   126Ôćĺ    synonyms: [string];
   127Ôćĺ    currentIndex: number;
   128Ôćĺ};
   129Ôćĺtype GetInnerType<S> = S extends SomeInterface<infer T> ? T : never
   130Ôćĺ
   131Ôćĺfunction getSynonym<K keyof SynonymCorpus>, (key: K, sources: GetInnerType<Synonym[K]>, peek: boolean = false): string;
   132Ôćĺ```
   133Ôćĺ
   134ÔćĺWhen a specific key is provided to the synonym system, it returns the next unreturned synonym. If no synonyms are left, it shuffles the list of synonyms, resets the currentIndex to 0 to mark the entire list as unreturned, then returns the next unreturned synonym.
