---

## Implementation Plan: `Chat.svelte` Full Rendering

This plan covers three coordinated changes: extracting `formatTime` to a shared module, implementing the full `Chat.svelte` component, and writing `Chat.svelte.spec.ts`.

---

### Design Decisions

**Where does `formatTime` live?**

`src/lib/time.ts` is the right location. It is a pure function with no component dependencies, and it will be needed by at least `Selector.svelte` and `Chat.svelte`. Making it a `.ts` module keeps it in the `$lib` tree, testable in the `server` vitest project (pure function, no DOM), and importable anywhere without circular concerns.

`Selector.svelte` currently defines it inline. After extraction, `Selector.svelte` just imports it. No behavior changes there.

**Should `formatTime` tests live separately?**

The vitest config splits by file pattern: `*.svelte.spec.ts` goes to the browser project, plain `*.spec.ts` goes to the node/server project. A `time.spec.ts` file would run in the node environment, which is ideal for a pure date utility. However the requirement asks only for `Chat.svelte.spec.ts`, so this is optional follow-up work, not in scope here.

**CSS class structure for message bubbles**

The natural structure is a list of message items, each with a role modifier. Mirroring Selector's pattern of BEM-ish flat classes:

```
.message-list          ÔÇö the <ul> wrapping all messages, no bullets
.message               ÔÇö each <li>
.message.user          ÔÇö user-sent bubble (right-aligned)
.message.partner       ÔÇö partner-sent bubble (left-aligned, with avatar)
.bubble                ÔÇö the text/timestamp container
.message-time          ÔÇö the timestamp within each bubble
```

For partner messages, the avatar sits to the left of the bubble, using a flex row. For user messages, the row is reversed (or just right-aligned with `margin-left: auto` on the bubble). The partner avatar reuses the same `.avatar` dimensions as Selector (40x40, border-radius 50%, `background: #ccc` fallback).

**The header section**

The header is `position: sticky; top: 0` so it stays visible while the message list scrolls beneath it within the `.chat` section. The header is `<header class="chat-header">` containing:
- `<div class="avatar-wrap">` with `<img class="avatar">` and `<span class="status-dot status--{chat.status}">`
- `<div class="chat-info">` with `<span class="chat-name">` and `<span class="chat-status-text">`

This parallels Selector's `.avatar-wrap` structure precisely, reusing the same mental model.

**Auto-scroll with `$effect`**

`$effect` in Svelte 5 re-runs whenever its reactive dependencies change. The right dependency to track is `chat.messages.length` (or the messages array itself). The implementation binds a reference to the messages container element via `bind:this`, then scrolls it to the bottom. The effect must run after the DOM update, which `$effect` guarantees (it runs after the component updates the DOM).

```ts
let messagesEl: HTMLUListElement;
$effect(() => {
    // Reading chat.messages.length makes this re-run on every new message
    chat.messages.length;
    messagesEl?.scrollTo({ top: messagesEl.scrollHeight });
});
```

Note: `messagesEl` is referenced without reactive declaration (`let` not `$state`) because we do not need reactivity on the element itself ÔÇö we only need to call a method on it. Using `$state` on a DOM ref would be unnecessary and unusual.

**Empty state**

When `chat.messages.length === 0`, render a `<p class="empty-state">` inside the message list area (not inside the `<ul>`, but as a sibling or conditional sibling). The text should feel tonally appropriate: "No messages yet. Say something." This is consistent with Selector's `.chat-preview.empty` handling but warrants its own class since it lives in a different context.

**Switching chats**

`chat` is `$derived(appState.chats[appState.currentlySelected])`, so everything in the template reactively updates when `currentlySelected` changes. The `$effect` for auto-scroll also re-runs because it reads `chat.messages.length`, which changes when the derived `chat` switches. No special handling needed.

**The `<section class="chat">` wrapper**

The outer wrapper must keep `class="chat"` because `+page.svelte` targets `.chat` with `:global(.chat) { flex: 1; overflow-y: auto; }`. The header inside it is `position: sticky; top: 0` so it sticks to the top of the scrolling `.chat` region.

---

### Step-by-Step Implementation

#### Step 1: Create `src/lib/time.ts`

This is a new file containing only `formatTime`. The implementation is a direct lift from `Selector.svelte`:

```ts
/** Format a message time: HH:MM if today, else "Mon DD". */
export function formatTime(date: Date): string {
    const now = new Date();
    const sameDay =
        date.getFullYear() === now.getFullYear() &&
        date.getMonth() === now.getMonth() &&
        date.getDate() === now.getDate();
    if (sameDay) {
        return date.toLocaleTimeString([], { hour: '2-digit', minute: '2-digit' });
    }
    return date.toLocaleDateString([], { month: 'short', day: 'numeric' });
}
```

#### Step 2: Update `src/lib/Selector.svelte`

Remove the inline `formatTime` definition from the `<script>` block. Add `import { formatTime } from './time.js';` at the top. No other changes.

#### Step 3: Implement `src/lib/Chat.svelte`

Full component structure:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
    import { appState } from './state.svelte.js';
    import { formatTime } from './time.js';

    const chat = $derived(appState.chats[appState.currentlySelected]);

    let messagesEl: HTMLUListElement;

    $effect(() => {
        // Depend on message count so this re-runs on each new message or chat switch
        chat.messages.length;
        messagesEl?.scrollTo({ top: messagesEl.scrollHeight });
    });
</script>

<section class="chat">
    <header class="chat-header">
        <div class="avatar-wrap">
            <img src={chat.profilePicture} alt={chat.name} class="avatar" />
            <span class="status-dot status--{chat.status}"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="chat-info">
            <span class="chat-name">{chat.name}</span>
            <span class="chat-status-text">{chat.statusText}</span>
        </div>
    </header>

    {#if chat.messages.length === 0}
        <p class="empty-state">No messages yet. Say something.</p>
    {:else}
        <ul class="message-list" bind:this={messagesEl}>
            {#each chat.messages as msg (msg.time)}
                <li class="message {msg.role}">
                    {#if msg.role === 'partner'}
                        <div class="avatar-wrap">
                            <img src={chat.profilePicture} alt={chat.name} class="avatar" />
                        </div>
                    {/if}
                    <div class="bubble">
                        <span class="bubble-text">{msg.text}</span>
                        <span class="message-time">{formatTime(msg.time)}</span>
                    </div>
                </li>
            {/each}
        </ul>
    {/if}
</section>
```

One subtlety: `bind:this={messagesEl}` only works when the `<ul>` is in the DOM. When messages is empty we render the empty state instead, so `messagesEl` will be undefined. The optional chaining `messagesEl?.scrollTo(...)` handles this safely.

A second subtlety: the key `(msg.time)` uses the `Date` object reference. Since `new Date()` produces unique objects per push (they will not share reference), this works correctly as a keyed each. An alternative is `(msg.time.toISOString())` for a string key, which is slightly more conventional for keyed each blocks when time granularity could theoretically produce collisions ÔÇö but for this game's usage, `time` is fine.

CSS (within `<style>`):

```css
.chat {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    /* flex: 1 and overflow-y: auto come from the parent via :global(.chat) */
}

.chat-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 8px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;
    background: white;
    position: sticky;
    top: 0;
    z-index: 1;
    flex-shrink: 0;
}

/* Reuse Selector's avatar pattern */
.avatar-wrap {
    position: relative;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    margin-right: 8px;
}
.avatar {
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    background: #ccc;
}
.status-dot {
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 1px;
    right: 1px;
    width: 10px;
    height: 10px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    border: 2px solid white;
}
.status--active  { background: #4caf50; }
.status--away    { background: #ff9800; }
.status--busy    { background: #f44336; }
.status--offline { background: #9e9e9e; }

.chat-info {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
}
.chat-name {
    font-weight: bold;
}
.chat-status-text {
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: #555;
}

.message-list {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 8px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 8px;
}

.message {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-end;
    gap: 6px;
}

/* User messages: push bubble to the right */
.message.user {
    justify-content: flex-end;
}

/* Partner messages: avatar on the left, bubble flows right */
.message.partner {
    justify-content: flex-start;
}

.bubble {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    max-width: 60%;
    padding: 6px 10px;
    border-radius: 12px;
}

.message.user .bubble {
    background: #0084ff;
    color: white;
    border-bottom-right-radius: 2px;
    align-items: flex-end;
}

.message.partner .bubble {
    background: #e9e9eb;
    color: #000;
    border-bottom-left-radius: 2px;
    align-items: flex-start;
}

.bubble-text {
    word-break: break-word;
}

.message-time {
    font-size: 0.7em;
    color: inherit;
    opacity: 0.65;
    margin-top: 2px;
}

.empty-state {
    padding: 16px;
    color: #999;
    font-style: italic;
    text-align: center;
}
```

Note on CSS duplication: `.avatar-wrap`, `.avatar`, `.status-dot`, and `.status--*` are duplicated from Selector. Since Svelte scopes styles per component, this is intentional and unavoidable without a shared CSS file or design tokens. The TDD explicitly calls for simplicity and minimal abstraction, so this is the right call for now.

#### Step 4: Write `src/lib/Chat.svelte.spec.ts`

The test file mirrors `Selector.svelte.spec.ts` in structure. It uses `vitest-browser-svelte` render, `page` from `vitest/browser`, and direct `document.querySelector` calls for class checks.

Key test structure:

```ts
import { page } from 'vitest/browser';
import { beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from 'vitest';
import { render } from 'vitest-browser-svelte';
import Chat from './Chat.svelte';
import { appState } from './state.svelte.js';
import { md } from './types.js';

describe('Chat', () => {
    beforeEach(() => {
        appState.currentlySelected = 0;
        // Reset Claudia's messages to empty before each test
        appState.chats[0].messages = [];
    });

    describe('header', () => {
        it('shows the partner name', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            await expect.element(page.getByText('Claudia')).toBeInTheDocument();
        });

        it('has an avatar image', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const avatar = document.querySelector('.chat-header .avatar');
            expect(avatar).not.toBeNull();
        });

        it('has a status dot', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const dot = document.querySelector('.chat-header .status-dot');
            expect(dot).not.toBeNull();
        });

        it('status dot class reflects partner status', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            // Claudia is 'active'
            const dot = document.querySelector('.chat-header .status-dot');
            expect(dot?.classList.contains('status--active')).toBe(true);
        });

        it('shows status text', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            await expect.element(page.getByText('Always here for you ÔÖí')).toBeInTheDocument();
        });
    });

    describe('empty state', () => {
        it('shows empty state when there are no messages', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const empty = document.querySelector('.empty-state');
            expect(empty).not.toBeNull();
        });

        it('does not render a message list when empty', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const list = document.querySelector('.message-list');
            expect(list).toBeNull();
        });
    });

    describe('messages', () => {
        beforeEach(() => {
            appState.chats[0].messages = [
                { role: 'partner', text: md('Hello there'), time: new Date() },
                { role: 'user',    text: md('Hi Claudia'),  time: new Date() }
            ];
        });

        it('renders all messages', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            await expect.element(page.getByText('Hello there')).toBeInTheDocument();
            await expect.element(page.getByText('Hi Claudia')).toBeInTheDocument();
        });

        it('partner messages have the .partner class', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const partnerMsgs = document.querySelectorAll('.message.partner');
            expect(partnerMsgs).toHaveLength(1);
        });

        it('user messages have the .user class', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const userMsgs = document.querySelectorAll('.message.user');
            expect(userMsgs).toHaveLength(1);
        });

        it('partner messages include an avatar', async () => {
            render(Chat);
            const partnerMsg = document.querySelector('.message.partner');
